<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-424-713  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 424 713.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Sept 11 1990 v4 n30 p16(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font Company adds advanced hinting to 1,400 PS fonts. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pfiffner, Pamela.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Font Company Inc. (product introduction).andO;Topic:     FontsUpgradingEnhancementsLibraries.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Pamela PfiffnerandM;Phoenix -- The Font Company has upgraded its PostScript font library toinclude features that take advantage of the improved screen-renderingtechnology of Adobe Type Manager 1.2 and, in the future, PostScript Level 2.andM;The company also said it plans to have 1,500 typefaces for the NeXTworkstation ready by the Seybold Computer Publishing Exposition in earlyOctober.andM;The Font Company's 1,400 fonts now will incorporate Type 1 hintingspecifications that have not been used before by any other font company,according to Dan Barthel, president of The Font Company.andP;  Hints arealgorithms that optimize fonts for resolutions of 300 dpi or lower.andP;  Thehints that The Font Company has added to its fonts improve screen appearanceand, with printers incorporating the ATM rasterizer, also improvelow-resolution output.andM;The company has added H-stem and V-stem hints that better define horizontaland vertical widths, respectively, when running under ATM 1.2, thesoon-to-be-released ATM 2.0 or on some low-resolution printers.andP;  Users willnotice the difference in typefaces with thin horizontal or vertical lines, inwhich one added pixel will dramatically alter its appearance, according toBarthel.andM;Printers that include ATM font-rendering technology in their PostScriptinterpreters -- such as Apple's new Personal LaserWriter NT, which usesVersion 51.8 of PostScript -- will take advantage of the new hints foroutput.andM;According to Rob Babcock, product marketing manager for Type 1 specificationsand PostScript Level 2 at Adobe Systems Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., thenew hints make fonts in small sizes &quot;visible at extremely low resolutions.&quot;andM;In January, The Font Company had converted its Type 3 fonts, which do notinclude hinting algorithms, into the Type 1 format.andP;  &quot;We've now remade everyface over a four-month period to include the new hints,&quot; Barthel said.andM;Registered owners of The Font Company's Type 1 fonts will receive theupgraded fonts free of charge.andM;The Font Company expects its complete type library to number 2,000 faces by1991.andP;  It strictly avoids regularizing its fonts.andP;  Regularizing is thepractice of evening out stem weights that often accompanies hinting.andP;  &quot;Wekeep true to the letter form,&quot; Barthel said.andM;The Font Company is located at 12629 N. Tatum Blvd., Suite 210, Phoenix,Ariz.andP;  85032; (602) 998-9711.andO;</TEXT></DOC>